{"format": "tiptap/v1", "updatedAt": "2026-06-22T12:16:50.311Z", "doc": {"type": "doc", "content": [{"type": "image", "attrs": {"src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,", "alt": "Normalization — concept overview"}}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "What Normalization Is"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Normalization"}, {"type": "text", "text": " in the context of vanishing and exploding gradients usually means "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Batch Normalization"}, {"type": "text", "text": " or "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Layer Normalization"}, {"type": "text", "text": ", both of which keep activations in a stable range so gradients are less likely to shrink or blow up during training. The basic idea is to make the values flowing through the network have more consistent scale, often by pushing them toward zero mean and unit variance.[][]"}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Why It Helps"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "When activations become too large, gradients can explode; when they become too small or get stuck in saturated regions, gradients can vanish. Normalization reduces this instability by keeping each layer’s inputs more predictable, which makes optimization smoother and helps the network learn faster.[]"}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "How It Works"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "A normalization layer typically does three things:"}]}, {"type": "orderedList", "attrs": {"start": 1, "type": null}, "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Centers"}, {"type": "text", "text": " the activations by subtracting the mean."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Scales"}, {"type": "text", "text": " them by dividing by the standard deviation."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Optionally applies learned shift and scale parameters so the model can still represent useful distributions.[][][]"}]}]}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "In Batch Normalization, this is computed over a mini-batch, while Layer Normalization computes it across features within a single example. In both cases, the goal is to keep activations from drifting into unstable ranges that make gradients problematic.[][][]"}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Why It Matters in Generative AI"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Normalization is widely used in deep networks for generative AI because these models are often very deep and sensitive to unstable training. In Transformers, for example, normalization is a major stabilizer that helps attention and feed-forward blocks train reliably. It does not directly solve the root math of vanishing gradients, but it makes training much more robust in practice.[][][]"}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Mental Model"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Think of normalization like a "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "traffic regulator"}, {"type": "text", "text": ". If every layer is sending values that are too big or too tiny, the regulator keeps them in a reasonable lane so the whole network can move smoothly.[][]"}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Key Takeaways"}]}, {"type": "bulletList", "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Normalization keeps activations at a more stable scale, often near "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "zero mean and unit variance"}, {"type": "text", "text": ".[][]"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "It helps reduce both vanishing and exploding gradient problems by preventing activations from drifting into bad ranges.[]"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Batch Normalization"}, {"type": "text", "text": " works across a mini-batch;"}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Layer Normalization"}, {"type": "text", "text": " works across features in one sample.[][]"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "It improves training stability and convergence, especially in deep and generative models.[]"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Normalization is a practical stabilizer, not a complete mathematical cure for gradient issues.[]"}]}]}]}]}}